07_BACKEND_ARCHITECTURE
Document ID: QH-007Version: 1.0 DraftStatus: Draft
Purpose
Define the backend architecture, responsibilities, boundaries, and implementation rules for Quant Hub.
Architectural Style
Use a modular monolith initially with clearly separated domains. Every domain can later be extracted into an independent service without major redesign.
Layers
Presentation/API LayerApplication LayerDomain LayerInfrastructure LayerPersistence Layer
Core Services
API GatewayAuthenticationConfigurationMarket DataResearchFeature EngineeringStrategy EngineBacktestingPaper TradingExecutionRiskPortfolioNotificationsMonitoringReporting
Dependency Rules
Dependencies flow inward only. UI never accesses the database directly. Domain logic never depends on frameworks. Infrastructure implements interfaces defined by the domain.
API Standards
REST using FastAPI. Version endpoints. Validate all requests with Pydantic. Return consistent error schemas. Document endpoints with OpenAPI.
Background Processing
Long-running tasks (data sync, backtests, ML jobs) execute asynchronously. Jobs are observable and retry transient failures.
Configuration
All runtime configuration comes from environment variables or version-controlled configuration files. No secrets in source code.
Logging & Observability
Structured logs, request IDs, execution metrics, health endpoints, audit logs for trading actions.
Security
Authentication required for protected APIs. Principle of least privilege. Input validation, rate limiting, secret management, dependency updates.
Scalability
Design service interfaces so engines can later run as independent services. Avoid tight coupling and shared mutable state.
Testing
Unit tests for business logic, integration tests for services, end-to-end tests for critical trading workflows.
Implementation Rules
No business logic in controllers. Services are small and focused. Repository pattern for persistence. Dependency injection for external resources.
Closing
The backend is the operational core of Quant Hub. Maintainability, observability, and correctness take precedence over premature optimization.